spanGrp.span: even if I ask you, you must not talk, even if I ask you
nǀake ng katyuuʼin a, a ǁu si ku a ǂxoa, [a] nǀake ng katyuuʼin a,
al vra ek jou, jy moenie praat nie, al vra ek jou
transcribed by ER in September 2008; last modified 02.02.2009; more or less OK, revised bz WI in Feb 2013 for DoBeS corpus project
/nǀa/ (or /nǀa ke/?): E says this means 'al' (dt.: 'ich frage euch schon'?!'); E has also used an explained it like this somewhere else; check!
check if /ka tyuuʼin/ always appears with the /ka/ particle => yes, it does!
E speaks to someone who sits next to her
E speaks to someone who sits next to her
you must not speak, I ? ask you
a ǁu si ǂxoa, nǀake katyuuʼin a,
jy moenie praat nie, al vra ek jou
E speaks to someone who sits next to her
once, a farmhand worked for the Boer
ǁʼuin a ko ke, [ǀʼhuunsi] ǀqhore xa siinsnn ǀʼhuunsi
ander dag het [die Boer] die hotnot by die Boer gewerk
E translates OBL either as 'by die Boer' or as 'vir die Boer'

"hotnot", is normally considered to be a racist term for coloured people in general, or for coloured or black people who work as servants on farms; but E does not know this negative connotation; for her, "hotnot", is the "normal", term for a servant, or "boy", who works on a farm

/ke/ sounds like [xe], but E says it is /ke/!; the /ke/ does not seem to be obligatory here, but it seems to belong to /ǁuin a ko/; check again, but I think /ke/ is alright here (E also repeats [ke]), and says /xe/ or /xae/ is wrong!, but she translates it as 'het', but then she also goes on with ku xae ku, what is not said in the next rec.!)
he (the Boer) says to the farmhand
I will just say (= call him) Jakob, (because) I don't know his name
ng si maar ku Jakob, ng ǁu ǁxaea ku ǀeen,
ek sal maar sê Jakob, (want) ek ken nie sy naam nie

Si and ER can't hear a /ka/ before /ǀeen/, but E says it must be there (E says ... ǁxaea ka ǀeen (know the name) would be possible, but /*...ǁxaea ku ǀeen/ is ungrammatical); /ka ǀeen/ seems to have an obligatory /ka/ prefix, even though it is hardly (or not at all) heard here (I have the same with F's /ka nǂoqno/ 'shadow' in Janniejannie)
E talks to the people that are listening
you must go to, you must go to ...
a si ǁʼae, [a si] a si ǁʼae, ng ng]
E confirms that there is no OBL marker after ǁʼae, the [ngngng] is just stuttered
go and give him this letter",
a ng ǁʼaa aaʼa kua ǂxanisi a",
loop gee vir hom hierdie brief",

E says the beginning and the middle is stuttered, it should beginn with /ǁʼann aa/; if the beginning is not 2SG, then there should be an -a IMP suffix somewhere; /-ʼa/ suffix on /aa/ was not repeated by E, but I can here something there; but might also be stuttered only?!
ng ng ng ǀʼhuun] ng ǀʼhuunsi,
E says /ǀhʼuunsi/ is the 'Boer', and /ǀʼhuunke/ is 'baas'; I am not convinced, and she should rather have said /ng ǀʼhuunke/ here (cf. next rec.)
E says /ǀhʼuunsi/ is the 'Boer', and /ǀʼhuunke/ is 'baas'; I am not convinced; the others have a different word for 'baas'
in repetition, /ǀʼhuunke/ somtimes sounds like [ǀʼhuunuke]; I have the same sometimes with /gunn-ke/ 'things' => [gunnuke]
(...) sounds more like /au ǀai .../; but E says it is /ku/; check again!
then you just sleep there (at baas Andries' farm)"
dan kan jy maar daar slaap",
alternative translation from E: 'dan moet jy maar daar slaap'
nice Imperative-construction; it should be OK like this; but check again, there was some variation when E repeated this
there he goes, (he) takes the letter, there he goes, (he) walks
ǁʼannʼa ku, ǀai ǂxanisi, ku ǁʼannʼa, ku dyaqnn,
daar gaan hy, vat (hy) die brief, daar gaan hy, (hy) stap
he still walks, he still goes to that farm, (when) the sun goes down
[ku nog] ku nog dyaqnn, ku nog ǁʼaa tya ǃkhaa, ǁʼuin ǀʼee,
hy loop nog, hy gaan nog na daardie plaas toe, toe gaan die son onder
but he just walks, walks, walks
maar ku maar dyaqnn, dyaqnn, dyaqnn,
maar hy loop maar nog, loop, loop
toe kom hy mos daar na ...

first time that I hear /ǁʼaa/ used as 'arrive at'; Geelmeidism?!; ? after a long discussion, E decided that he has probably arrived at the farm and is now maybe at the gate (what is context only, and not said explictly), and then he goes (from the gate etc.) to the Boer's house; check!
but the sun has already set
maar die son het al ondergegaan

alternatively repeated by E as: /nou ǁʼuin ke al ǀʼeea/ = 'nou die son is al (klaar) onder/die son het al onder gegaan'; the whole record sounds somehow different, but E seems to be quite sure about it
[ng ...] ng ǀʼhuunsi ke xa ǀaea ng
sounds like [ǂxanisi gee/ke] - [ǂxanisi gee a] => [gee] might be the same as /dyee/; Sven hears [gyee]
check; 'is the 'verb' the same as in the preceding record?? /ǂxanisi dyee a/? or is it /ǂxanisi ke a/? might be the first one, since E's /ke/ often sounds more like [tye]
he gives the letter to the Boer
hy gee die Boer die brief
E says it is /ǀʼhuunsi ǀai ǂxanisi/; the beginning seems to be stuttered; E is quite sure about it, so this is probably wat she wanted to say
he says "Jakob, do you (want to) go back again?"
hy sê "Jakob, wil jy weer omdraai?"
first translation from E: 'Jakob, wil jy weer omdraai'; alternative: "Jakob, gaan jy weer terug?"
very nice: Baas Andries has the /ha/ pronoun, while Jakob is /ku/! it is similar as in Janniejannie, where different pronouns are used for different discourse participants
my master said I (should) just sleep (here)
ǀʼhuunsi ke xa kua, ng maar ʘunn,
my baas het gesê ek kan maar slaap
but I see, I see I still can walk, I (can) ...
maar nǀai, nǀai, si nog maar dyaqnn, ng
maar ek sien, ek sien ek kan maar nog loop,gaan, ek (kan) ...
E says [ǁʼae nǁng] and [ǁʼaa nǁng] would both be OK
/ǁʼae nǁng/ might be a loan translation from Afrikaans; there is also a word /ǁʼaru/ that means 'go home'
"nee baas, ek gaan maar huis toe",
E also repeats /ng si maar ǁʼae nǁng/; the /si/ is not here; /ǁʼaa/ und /ǁʼae/ seem to be interchangable again!
the Boer says "yes, then walk now!
die Boer sê "ja, nou loop maar!
(he) greets the Boer, there he walks
nebeke ǀʼhuunsi, ng ǁʼannʼa ku dyaqnn,
(hy) groet die Boer, daar loop hy
E says there is no OBL marker here, the two [ng] probably phonetically again
[gǁaa ke a gǁaa ke al e,
E says she stutters a bit
what is the al-e / e at the end?
he walks, he walks, he walks, he walks, he walks
ku dyaqnn, ku dyaqnn, ku dyaqnn, ku dyaqnn, ku dyaqnn,
toe loop hy, loop hy, loop hy, loop hy
check English translation; (etwa: "wie der Teufel es so will ...?)
he makes that you get thirsty
ha [kxʼuu] kxʼuu, [nǀa] nǀa a khinn ǁʼuin,
hy maak lat jy dors word
suddenly, he is nou thirsty, he ...
hy is nou skierlik dors, hy ...
he walks, again, then he comes (and) he sees
ku gǀoe dyaqnn, ku saa, ku nǀai,
toe kom loop hy weer, toe sien hy

this is the exact translation given by E: "toe kom loop hy weer, toe sien hy",; what is the /saa/ 'come' here? does it really belong to /dyaqnn/, and why? alternative translation by E: 'hy kom loop aan en hy sien'
there is mos a fire, it shines there
ǀʼii ke mos nǁaa, ha ǀqaa ng ki nǁaa,
daar is mos 'n vuur, hy lig daar
first translation by E: 'daar lig mos vuur'

E says you can't just say /nǁaa/ at the end of the second part (instead of /ng ki nǁaa/), but the /ng ki/ is obligatory before /nǁaa/ here; it cannot be left out (/*ha ǀqaa (ng) nǁaa/ is ungrammatical acc. to E); what system is behind that?
ay, I am already thirsty, I just want to go there and ask for water
ai, [ng reeds] ng reeds khinn ǁʼuin, tog ǂaoa ng ǁʼng ǃʼhoeʼa ǃkhaa ng tyoxoe,
ai, ek is reeds dors, nou ek wil tog daar loop water vra
/ǁʼnn/ or /ǁʼng/ is 'loop' here; E says it is not the same as /ǁʼann/; in the ditransitive elicitation most speakers gave /ǃʼhuiʼin - ǃʼhoeʼa/ etc. for 'ask for'
he walks, he walks, he walks, he ...
ku dyaqnn, ku dyaqnn, ku dyaqnn, ku
hy loop, hy loop, hy loop, hy ...
arrives, he sees that there is a farm
nǁae saa, ku nǀaa, [ǃkhaa ke] ǃkhaa ke mos he a,
?was für eine Struktur ist das denn? check again!
toe(t) hy kom toe sien hy maar is mos 'n plaas hierdie
the /e/ is almost always repeated by E; nevertheless, in one or two repetitions it was left out; what does it mean?? or is it /he a/?!
yes, there is a Boer's house, here it stands
ng, ǀʼhuunsi nǁng ke ha nǃaaʼa,
I first had /nǃaaǁʼa/ (did E repeat it like that?), but it is [nǃaaʼa] only
(hy) loop na die Boer se huis toe
sound just like [ǁʼuu ǂaqe], but E says this is /ǁʼaa ku ǂaqe/; probably OK
toe sien (hy) 'n Boerevrou sit kama daar

E said first 'ou Boerevrou' for /ǀʼhuunsi ǁʼorake/, but then she said just 'Boerevrou' is also OK; but it seems that the ǁʼorake is reserved for elder people, and, as E said, this term cannot be used to refer to a 'meisie'
the /ǀʼhuun(si)/ is hardly to be heard, but there is "something", like [huun] there; I transcribe it, since /ǀʼhuunsi/ is heavily reduced by E on other occasions as well
sounds like [ha ka ǁqann], but E rejects that there is a /ka/ present; she says it is stuttered again
nice: the 'old white woman' gets the /ha/ pronoun again (not /ku/); cf. also following records
nor sure if first /ha/ is really there
puts on (or: ?has put) on) her glasses, she sits and looks
gǃau ǁhoo ha brilsi, ha kama soo, ha ǂaqe,
sit haar brill op, sy kama sit en kyk
not sure if it is /ǁhooa ha/, /ǁhoo ha/ or just /ǁhooa brilsi/; check tense and possessive pronoun again!
last version by E was /ǁhoo ha brilsi/ 'sy sit haar bril op', at the beginning, it was 'sy het haar bril op'; this was also repeated on the next day (/ǁhoo ha/ 'sy sit op')
check again; E did not really understand herself
/ou nooi/ ['missie, old mistress] is the female counterpart of /baas/
"ay, missie, I want a bit of water",
"ai, ou nooi, na ǂaoa ǃqhaa ʘuni",
"ai, ou nooi, ek wil 'n bietjie water hê",
E repeats as /ǀʼhuunsi ǁʼorake nǁaa ka/
"okay, I go and fetch water for you", when she speaks, fire ...
"okay, ng ǁʼang ǀaa ǃkhaa", [nǁaa] ha nǁae ǂxoa, ǀʼii
okay, ek loop haal water vir jou", as sy praat, vuur ...
E repeats /okay, na .../, I hear /okay, ng .../; check again
nice: the witch has /ha/ as pronoun; the corresponding OBL for is here /nǁaa/ (see next record)
ER: /ǀaa/ here as the APPL form of /ǀai/?!
E says /ǁʼaa/ is not the same as /ǁʼ(a)ng/; /nǁae/ seems to mean 'when, while' here; cf. also rec. 090; is this a regular pattern?
nice: the witch has /ha/ as pronoun; the corresponding OBL for is here /nǁng/ (see also preceding record!)
check if E repeats /ng nǁaa/; actually, the /ng/ is not really audible
he sees, this is mos a ghost here
ku nǀai, ǀhoqo ke mos he a,
toe sien hy, (dit) is mos 'n duiwel hier
on the first day, E translated /ǀhoqo/ as 'duiwel', the next day as 'spook', and she said ''witch' would also be OK; I think 'ghost' is a better translation than 'devil' in English'
when the white woman goes to this side (= away, to fetch water)
ǀʼhuunsi ǁʼoraki nǁae dyaqnn ǁʼaa ǀxaa a,
toe die ou wit vrou díe kant toe loop ...
/nǁae/ seems to mean 'when, while' here; cf. also rec. 087
it seems as if /ku nǁau ǃae would be better/ (2009: why?)
hy harloop, daar die ou Boer vrou ...
[...] ǂkhai siia, [mos ǀhoqo] a ǀhoqo mos he
kom vinnig, sy is mos 'n duiwel, dis mos 'n duiwel
E repeats /saa/ instead of /sii/. I hear /sii, a/ or /siia/; E also once repeats /he/ instead of /e/; check!
check translationa dn structure again; the /a mos ǀhoqo a/ might be "wrong", and E corrects herself to /a ǀhoqo mos e/?!
"come take the water that you asked for",
"kom vat die water wat jou gevra het",
sounds different; check again, especially if /ǀai/ is really /ǀai/
the white woman says "take the water that you asked for
ǀʼhuunsi ǁʼorake ka, "ǀaia ǃqhaa ha a ǃʼhoeʼa,
die ou nooi sê "kom vat die water wat jy gevra het
check if the /a/ is supposed to be in again!
E says /ka/ and /ku/ is the same, both means 'say'
na amper ǀaia ng [gǀa] gǀa broekusi se ǀuutyuu",
ek vat amper aan jou broek se gat (= sterte)"
'vat aan' in translation corresponds nicely with OBL marker; is this again an Afrikaanism or Geelmeidism?
E repeats /ǀai-a/, but I do not hear an /-a/ suffix
E also repeats [broek-e-si], but it sounds more like [broek-u-si] here
hy hardloop maar hy take se rug out
das Wort hat irgendetwas mit Holkreuz machen beim laufen zu tun
he runs, he runs, he runs, he runs
ǃae, ku ǃae, ku ǃae, ku ǃae,
hy hardloop, hy hardloop, hy hardloop, hy hardloop
the white woman says "take the water that you asked for
ǀʼhuunsi ǁʼorake ka, "ǀaia ǃqhaa ha ǃʼhoeʼa,
die ou nooi sê "vat die water wat jou gevra het
I don't hear the /ha a/ here; sounds just like /ng/
na amper ǀaia [gǀa] gǀa broekesi se ǀuutyuu", huu,
ek vat amper an jou broek se gat",
huu, the thing (= Jakob) runs, the thing runs
(he) runs into the house (= his parents' house)
(toe) loop hardloop (hy) in die huis in
he goes and lies down, he dies (is unconsciuos)
E explains Jakob is not really dead, he is just "flou", ('weak; unconscious, insensible; dead-tired')
/tyoa/ = 'klaar wees', /tyoan'a/ = 'be absent'; not the same; checked with E; check also with other speakers
E says there is a /ha/ between the two words (/ǀhoqo ha tyoanʼa/); I don't hear anything
went back (or: turned around), or he disappeared from there
khaʼua, of ha ǁuni ng tyoxoe,
is terug of hy is daar weg
stands up, "what is this, what is this?"
spring op, "wat is dit, wat is dit?"
E translates as 'opspring', but the verb just means 'stand up, get up'
ER: /ǀʼaa tyaa/ 'lê dood' means here 'he is unconscious' (SVC)
(they) struggle with him, struggle with him, (until) the sun comes out
[... ...] ǃxana nǀa ku, ǃxana nǀa ku, ǁʼuin ǁʼng,
(hulle) sukkel met hom, sukkel met hom, toe die son uitkom
beginn is false start according to E
the sun goes along, it comes out, it goes along, it goes along, goes along
ǁʼuin ǃare, ha ǁʼng, ha ǃare, ha ǃare, ǃare,
die son kom uit, en die son kom verby, en verby, en verby
sounds like [ǃare] but in slow repetition with E it is [ǃere] = 'verbygaan'; Sands has /ǃere/, dic (347) has /ǃare/;
E imitates here the stuttering of the scared Jakob
there seems to be no OBL!!! it is definitely NOT repeated by E, so the [ng] might just be 'stt...st..uttered'
E imitates here the stuttering of the scared Jakob
his father says "but you know there is no farm there",
ku ainki kua, "(...) mos ǁxaea ǃqhaa ǁu nǁaa tyoxoe,
sy pa sê "jy weet mos daar is nie 'n plaas nie
(...): there is a click , but E repeats just /a mos ǁxaea .../ 'jy weet mos'; it might probably just be stuttered again, but check!
the path (...) the Boer's farm, (...) not find another ?house
ǃann ke [neti mos] (...) ǀʼhuunsi ǃqhaa (...) ǁu nog hoo nǁng
die pad (...) die Boer se plaas, (...) kry nie nog 'n huis nie

E repeats /ǃann ke mos neti hoo ng ǀʼhuunsi ǃkhaa, nǁng ke ǁu nǁaa tya xoe??? hoo nǁng/; 'the path just comes from the Boer's [baas Andries'] farm, ???', die pad kom net van [baas Andries se] die Boer se plaas af, [maar] daar is nie [nog] 'n huis nie
B repeated /ku nou tyoa/, but there seems to be a click at the end; very softly spoken
he (Jakob) stands up, and now he sits down
ku maar khuuǁʼng, ku nou suin,
toe staan hy maar op, en hy sit nou
(father) "but the Boer said, or did the Boer not say you (must) go and sleep (there)?"
"ǀʼhuunsi ke mos xa kua, of ǀʼhuunsi ǁam xa kua, ǁʼaa ʘunn",
"die Boer het mos gesê, of het die Boer nie gesê nie, jy moet loop slaap?"
"die Boer het gesê ek moet slaap
but I just thought I should just turn around",
maar xa maar ǂʼain, si maar khaʼu",
maar ek het maar gedink ek moet maar omdraai",
/ǂain/ here without the /-ka/ suffix; why? because of past?; the click is missing, too; sound like /... maar ngkesi maar .../
